Reference runner for the `rescm_relax_ref` benchmark.

  reference.py   mlsynth's runner: the authors' scmrelax L2RelaxationCV on a
                 deterministic toy factor panel at a single, matched relaxation
                 level tau (half of eta-bar, the equal-weight feasibility level).
                 Reproduces the panel the Python case generates and emits the
                 reference L2 weight vector. Produces the captured bundle.
                 scmrelax's hardcoded MOSEK solver is routed to the open CLARABEL
                 solver (the L2 relaxation is a convex QP with a unique,
                 solver-invariant optimum).

  (No vendored data: the panel is generated deterministically in reference.py.)

Reference
  The reference is Liao-Shi-Zheng's relaxed-balanced synthetic control. It is
  available as BOTH:
    * github.com/YapengZheng/Relaxed_SC   -- the original author code (Yapeng
      Zheng).
    * github.com/metricshilab/scmrelax    -- the packaged version of that same
      Relaxed_SC code (the installable `scmrelax` package, used here).
  scmrelax hardcodes the commercial MOSEK solver; because the L2 relaxation is a
  plain convex QP with a unique optimum, the runner transparently routes those
  solves to the open CLARABEL solver. The optimum was independently confirmed
  with CLARABEL, ECOS, OSQP and SCS (all agree to solver precision).

Source
  Liao, Wei, Zhentao Shi & Yapeng Zheng (2026), "A Relaxation Approach to
  Synthetic Control" (arXiv 2508.01793). All credit to the authors. This file
  produces the captured reference bundle only and is not part of the mlsynth
  library.
